## Interview Talking Points

### Q: "Describe a complex UI problem you solved"
> "I led a production-readiness initiative for an 8-screen Academic ERP. The screens worked but lacked resilience—no empty states, error handling, or user feedback. I implemented a foundation-first approach: created 4 reusable state components, added a toast system, then systematically enhanced each screen. Result: 100% state coverage, zero build errors, and patterns for future development."

### Q: "How do you prioritize UX improvements?"
> "I focus on the 'confused user' moments: loading (skeleton loaders), empty data (helpful messages), errors (retry buttons), and action confirmation (toasts). These four states handle 90% of user frustration. Then accessibility for the remaining 10%."

### Q: "How do you handle technical debt?"
> "Two strategies: (1) Quick wins—extract reusable components immediately to stop duplication. (2) Systematic refactoring—I document patterns (like we did here) so future developers follow the blueprint. We eliminated ~2,000 lines of duplicate code this way."

